## 4. How APS should begin when only Sales Orders exist

You said the only thing available today is a list of Sales Orders.

That is enough to start.

### Input object

A Sales Order should contain at least:

* SO number
* customer
* due date
* quantity
* grade
* section / dimension / size
* route or process family if known
* priority / urgency
* optional commercial weight / service class

### APS should not ask the planner to manually build everything

The planner should not be forced to manually review and hand-pick every order every time. That does not scale.

Instead, APS should first auto-select a **planning horizon**.

Examples:

* due in next 3 days
* due in next 7 days
* due in next 10 days
* overdue + next 5 days
* manually pinned urgent orders + next 7 days

The later discussion correctly identifies this as a missing piece: who picks the initial SO set? The answer should be: **the system proposes the set using horizon rules**, and the planner can override. 

---

## 5. Lot formation is the heart of APS

The earlier discussions rightly reached the point that the real intelligence is not just in scheduling. It is in **how the system proposes lots**.  

This is the correct position.

### APS must propose manufacturing lots using rules like:

* same or compatible grade first
* compatible size / section / route
* due-date proximity
* minimum / maximum lot size
* heat-size constraint
* customer / dispatch coherence if relevant
* urgent order protection
* already-started or frozen material protection

### Planning objective of lot formation

The lot-formation stage should strike a balance between:

* on-time delivery
* manageable number of lots
* good upstream batching
* lower changeovers
* realistic resource loading

### What a Planning Order is

A Planning Order is a manufacturable lot proposal. It is not necessarily:

* one SO
* one heat
* one final MES production order

It is a planning object that says:

> “these SOs, in this quantity and compatibility envelope, should be treated together for planning and scheduling.”

That is the right role of Planning Orders in APS.

---

## 6. Heat-aware batching must be explicit

Steel planning cannot stop at abstract planning lots.

The system must derive heat requirements.

### Why

Because upstream production is constrained by:

* physical heat size
* grade compatibility
* transition constraints
* upstream resource availability
* casting continuity or batch rules if applicable

### Correct way to think about it

Do not say:

* “ignore heats and just schedule POs”
* or “heats replace planning orders entirely”

Instead say:

* Planning Orders express manufacturable lots
* APS derives the required heats needed to fulfill those lots
* those heats are then scheduled on actual upstream resources

### Important mapping note

Do not assume 1:1 mapping between objects.

Possible relationships:

* 1 SO → multiple Planning Orders
* multiple SOs → 1 Planning Order
* 1 Planning Order → multiple heats
* 1 heat → contributes to multiple SO allocations
* released execution orders may sit at heat level, lot level, or stage level depending on the system design

That complexity must be acknowledged up front.

---

## 7. What “campaign” should mean in the new APS

The word “campaign” can still exist in the UI if users understand it, but it must be redefined.

### Campaign must NOT mean:

* one giant grade-wise backlog block
* all same-grade demand clubbed together
* a serial object that forces the next group to wait

### Campaign may mean:

* a short-horizon sequence block
* a planner-approved bundle of lots
* a visible grouping for release and review
* a batch of compatible work chosen for a given planning window

So if the UI wants to preserve familiar language, that is acceptable. But the internals should not be driven by a rigid campaign-first architecture.

---

## 8. The scheduler must be finite and resource-driven

Once lots and heat requirements are available, the scheduler must solve a **finite-capacity** problem.

### Minimum scheduling considerations

* resource non-overlap
* operation precedence
* alternate resources if available
* setup / transition penalties
* due-date penalties
* freeze / lock constraints for committed work
* work already started
* optional split or no-split rules
* planning horizon and rescheduling limits

### What not to do

Do not hard-code giant sequential chains like:

* campaign A ends before campaign B starts
* campaign B ends before campaign C starts

unless those are true physical constraints, which in most of this discussion they were not.

### What to do instead

Let the scheduler decide sequence using:

* finite resource constraints
* changeover penalty matrices
* due-date penalties
* priority weights

That is where the real optimization should happen.

---

## 9. Manual intervention — what planners should control

The planner should control policy and exceptions, not micromanage every machine move by default.

### Planner should be able to control:

* planning horizon
* objective priorities
* urgent customer override
* forced include / exclude orders
* split / merge decisions for selected lots
* whether to allow partial fulfillment
* freeze already committed work
* acceptable lateness vs setup tradeoff
* preferred resource if needed

### Planner should not be expected to:

* manually build every heat from scratch
* manually pick each order from an 81-order backlog every cycle
* manually create the whole machine-level schedule unless resolving an exception

The correct operating model is:

> system proposes → planner adjusts → system reschedules → planner releases

