## 10. Recommended practical APS workflow

This is the workflow Claude should implement.

### Step 1 — Order Pool

Display backlog of Sales Orders with filters:

* due date
* priority
* grade
* section / size
* customer
* route family
* status

System suggests a default planning horizon, for example next 7 days.

### Step 2 — Planning Board

System auto-selects candidate SOs in the window.

Then it proposes Planning Orders by applying rules such as:

* grade compatibility
* due-date closeness
* size / route compatibility
* lot-size and heat-size feasibility

Planner can:

* merge
* split
* pin
* exclude
* force urgent inclusion

### Step 3 — Heat Builder

System derives heat requirements from the Planning Orders:

* heats needed
* expected tonnage per heat
* partial allocations
* compatibility warnings
* likely transitions

Planner can review and override only where required.

### Step 4 — Finite Scheduler

System generates a schedule on actual resources:

* SMS
* RM
* other included stages

Optimization objective may be a weighted combination of:

* on-time delivery
* reduced grade changeovers
* maximized throughput
* minimized WIP
* minimized rescheduling instability

### Step 5 — Review Board

Planner reviews:

* total tons planned
* due-date service level
* late orders
* transition count
* resource utilization
* bottlenecks
* conflicts
* frozen vs rescheduled work

### Step 6 — Release

Approved work is released to execution.

At release, the system should create the execution-level objects required by MES / shop floor:

* production orders
* heat instructions
* operation tasks
* dispatch sequence
  depending on plant design.

